Article 2 general obligations (b) — Reproductive health and family planning policies and programs

- States Parties may prohibit specific reproductive health services under laws, regulations or policies in order to achieve public or individual health aims, but they shall not do so if the prohibition interferes with access to comprehensive reproductive health services, violates the right to health of persons, or is discriminatory in any way. Such laws, regulations or policies must not limit access to these services: other, less restrictive means shall be sought for the fulfilment of these aims.
- States Parties shall effect the prohibition of all forms of discrimination and violence against women or activities deliberately inflicting pain or suffering against women or intentionally causing death to women, in choosing and exercising their reproductive health and family planning decisions.

Comments

Regional, in particular, civil society organizations should underscore their governments’ obligation to provide FCHV, LFC and other young friendly services, including family planning in a gender-sensitive analysis.

Article 3 — Provide the full range of health facilities and services

- States Parties shall, in accordance with international human rights standards and within their resources, develop and implement policies to ensure access to health education facilities including FCHV, LFC and other education and medical services relating to the reproductive system. These policies shall in particular guarantee, on a basis of equality of men and women, the training of health professionals to provide services consistent with Article 4 and Article ? (a).
